explore.taxonomy.BF3

M Fisher

1/21/2021

Description

Explorative plots looking at taxonomic assignments from BF3 sequences.

Set up


This script requires the following packages:

library(here)
library(tidyverse)
library(magrittr)
library(cowplot)


User directories

indir_blast  <- 'test-lane-1/data/blast'
indir_asv    <- 'test-lane-1/data/dada2/BF3'
indir_meta   <- 'test-lane-1/data/cutadapt/BF3'
outdir       <- 'test-lane-1/results'


Which marker is being analyzed?

marker <- 'BF3'


What are the names of the processed blast file with taxonomy from script 6?

# hashes with unique staxids
infile1 <- 'lane1_bf3_blast_uniqueIDs_taxonomy.csv'

# hashes with multiple IDs, that required the LCA function
infile2 <- 'lane1_bf3_blast_multipleIDs_taxonomy.csv'

Sequencing sample metadata, so that we can connect sample name (actually a number; in the ASV table) to sample ID.

metadat <- read_csv(here(indir_meta, paste0('cutadapt_output_metadata_',marker,'.csv')))
## Rows: 34 Columns: 4
## -- Column specification --------------------------------------------------------
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (3): Locus, file1, file2
## dbl (1): Sample_name
## 
## i Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## i Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
metadat %<>% dplyr::select(Sample_name, file1) %>%
  mutate(SampleID=str_remove(file1,"_L001_R1_001.fastq.fastq")) %>%
  mutate(SampleID=str_remove(SampleID,paste0("Locus_",marker,"_",marker,"_"))) %>%
  mutate(SampleID=str_sub(SampleID,start=1, end=-5)) %>%
  mutate(Group=ifelse(SampleID %in% c("Kangaroo","PCRNegative","SpeedVacNegative"), "Control", str_sub(SampleID, start=1,end=4))) %>%
  mutate(Group=ifelse(Group!="WASS",Group,ifelse(grepl("2020",SampleID),"WASS 2020", "WASS 2018"))) %>%
  dplyr::select(-file1)

combine & quality check

dat <- bind_rows(mdat,rdat,fdat)


1. Make sure that each hash has only one set of taxonomic information

checkdat <- dat %>% 
  group_by(Sample_name,Hash,dataset) %>%
  summarise(count=n(), .groups="drop") %>%
  filter(count > 1)
checkdat

It looks like all of those with a 2 count have matching taxonomy between the two unique IDs, but one row of taxonomic info is more fine-scale than the other. Save only the most specific taxonomic info.

## rows to remove have the most NAs
checkdat %<>% left_join(dat,by=c("Sample_name","Hash","dataset")) %>%
  arrange(desc(rowSums(is.na(.)))) %>%
  distinct(Sample_name,dataset, .keep_all = TRUE)

## remove those rows
dat %<>% anti_join(checkdat, by=c("Sample_name","Hash", "dataset","rank", "taxon"))

rm(checkdat)

  group_by(Sample_name,Hash,dataset) %>%
  summarise(count=n(), .groups="drop") %>%
  filter(count > 1)

2. Find the number of hashes with missing taxonomic information
Forward reads tend to have fewer successful taxonomic IDs, except for several technical replicates for one WACO 2021 crab / two Dungies / one WASS 2020 crab. Merged reads tend to have the most successful taxonomic IDs. Across all crab, there are a very high proportion of hashes that arent successfully assigned a taxonomy, but usuall <= 25% of reads. I have a feeling thats because a large number of reads come from very few hashes especially hashes that come from predator DNA.

Ratios

A quick look at the proportion of reads belonging to each taxa, for every sample.

# don't want NAs showing up in the plots
dat2 <- filter(dat, !is.na(rank))


Controls

What DNA did we pick up in the controls?

control_dat <- dat2 %>% filter(Group=="Control")




It looks like the green crab DNA goteverywhere. The rest is mostly bacteria. The weirdest thing is that there isnt any kangaroo DNA in the positive control??

Algae species in the negative controls:

  1. Planosiphon gracilis, a brown algae

  2. Pseudoralfsia verrucosa, a brown algae

Algae species only in the kangaroo:

  1. 68 reads of Bangiophyceae (class; phylum=Rhodophyta), a red algae, in kangaroo

Get a list of taxa from the negative controls, to remove from the samples:

taxa_to_remove <- control_dat %>%
  filter(SampleID %in% c("PCRNegative","SpeedVacNegative")) %>%
  filter(!(taxon %in% c("Carcinus maenas","Carcinus aestuarii"))) %>%
  pull(taxon)



Predator v Prey

How much predator DNA did we pick up, from each sample?

First, get total reads per sample so that we can calculate proportion of reads per taxon.

total_reads_per_sample <- dat2 %>%
  group_by(Group,SampleID,dataset) %>%
  summarise(total_reads=sum(nReads), .groups="drop")


Green Crab

egc_dat <- dat2 %>%
  filter(Group %in% c("WACO","WASS 2020", "WASS 2018")) %>%
  # remove all taxa in the negative controls, except green crab
  filter(!(taxon %in% taxa_to_remove))

egc_pred <- egc_dat %>%
  mutate(Predator=ifelse(taxon == "Carcinus maenas" | taxon == "Carcinus aestuarii",1,0)) %>%
  group_by(Group,SampleID,dataset,Predator) %>%
  summarise(sumReads=sum(nReads)) %>%
  left_join(total_reads_per_sample,by=c("Group","SampleID","dataset")) %>%
  mutate(pReads=sumReads/total_reads)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Group', 'SampleID', 'dataset'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.



Dungies

dungy_dat <- dat2 %>%
  filter(Group=="MARP") %>%
  filter(!(taxon %in% taxa_to_remove))

dungy_pred <- dungy_dat %>%
  mutate(Predator=ifelse(taxon == "Metacarcinus magister",1,0)) %>%
  group_by(Group,SampleID,dataset,Predator) %>%
  summarise(sumReads=sum(nReads)) %>%
  left_join(total_reads_per_sample,by=c("Group","SampleID","dataset")) %>%
  mutate(pReads=sumReads/total_reads)

Diet Composition

Green Crab

Remove predator DNA, and bacteria that werent captured in the negative controls. then recalculate total reads.

egc_prey <- egc_dat %>%
  mutate(Predator=ifelse(taxon == "Carcinus maenas" | taxon == "Carcinus aestuarii",1,0)) %>%
  filter(Predator==0) %>%
  filter(!(phylum %in% c("Actinobacteria","Bacteroidetes","Planctomycetes","Proteobacteria")))


egc_prey_total_reads <- egc_prey %>%
  group_by(Group,SampleID,dataset) %>%
  summarise(total_reads=sum(nReads))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Group', 'SampleID'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Weird, it almost looks like WACO_2021_001a should be the positive control???

The wolf DNA in WACO_2021_002c is contamination from SEFS. Lets remove the Chordata DNA for now.

egc_prey %<>% filter(phylum!="Chordata")

egc_prey_total_reads <- egc_prey %>%
  group_by(Group,SampleID,dataset) %>%
  summarise(total_reads=sum(nReads))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Group', 'SampleID'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.


Ok, with the new prey data set:

So we have lots of Dungeness crab and Hemigrapsus reads (plus crab that couldnt be IDd to genus, Malacostraca). But there are also some other cool things:

  • amphipods: Ampithoe lacertosa
  • copepods: Amphiascopsis cinctus
  • ostracods: Cyprideis torosa
  • worms: Algaophenia tubulifera
  • barnacles (Balanus)
  • bivalves: Mya spp. are soft-shell clams; Ruditapes are little-neck clam (yay!!!!)

Also, really crazy portunion conformis is a parasitic isopod, often found in shore crab hosts


Summarise and save the prey data

egc_prey_summary <- egc_prey %>%
  separate(col=SampleID, into=c("Crab","replicate"), sep=-1,remove=FALSE) %>%
  left_join(egc_prey_total_reads,by=c("Group","SampleID","dataset")) %>%
  mutate(pReads=nReads/total_reads) %>%
  group_by(taxon,kingdom,phylum,class,order,family,genus,species,dataset,score) %>%
  summarise(nCrabs=length(unique(Crab)), nReplicates=length(unique(SampleID)), total_reads=sum(nReads), mean_pReads=mean(pReads), sd_pReads=sd(pReads),
            SampleIDs=paste0(SampleID,collapse=","))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'taxon', 'kingdom', 'phylum', 'class', 'order', 'family', 'genus', 'species', 'dataset'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
write.csv(egc_prey_summary, here(outdir,"BF3_BLAST_prey_taxa_EGC.csv"), row.names=FALSE)
